04894nam a22007575i 9780691187976DE-B159720190523123322.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190523s2018    nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806911879767 a10.1515/97806911879762doi  a(DE-B1597)501823  a(OCoLC)1076406084  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aJC573.2.U6bC75 2008eb 7aBIO0220002bisacsh 7aHIS0360602bisacsh 7aPOL0420202bisacsh04a320.520922221 aCritchlow, Donald T., eauthor.10aPhyllis Schlafly and Grassroots Conservatism :bA Woman's Crusade /cDonald T. Critchlow. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2005  a1 online resource   atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPolitics and Society in Modern America ;v3800tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tCHAPTER ONE: The Making of a Grassroots Conservative -- tCHAPTER TWO: Ideology and Politics in 1952 -- tCHAPTER THREE: Anticommunism: A Young Woman's Crusade -- tCHAPTER FOUR: The Republican Right Under Attack -- tCHAPTER FIVE: The Goldwater Campaign -- tCHAPTER SIX: The Establishment Purges Schlafly -- tCHAPTER SEVEN: Confronting the Soviets in a Nuclear Age -- tCHAPTER EIGHT: Nixon Betrays the Right -- tCHAPTER NINE: The ERA Battle Revives the Right -- tCHAPTER TEN: The Triumph of the Right -- tCHAPTER ELEVEN: Ideology and Power in a Divided Nation -- tManuscript Collections -- tNotes -- tIndex  aLongtime activist, author, and antifeminist leader Phyllis Schlafly is for many the symbol of the conservative movement in America. In this provocative new book, historian Donald T. Critchlow sheds new light on Schlafly's life and on the unappreciated role her grassroots activism played in transforming America's political landscape. Based on exclusive and unrestricted access to Schlafly's papers as well as sixty other archival collections, the book reveals for the first time the inside story of this Missouri-born mother of six who became one of the most controversial forces in modern political history. It takes us from Schlafly's political beginnings in the Republican Right after the World War II through her years as an anticommunist crusader to her more recent efforts to thwart same-sex marriage and stem the flow of illegal immigrants. Schlafly's political career took off after her book A Choice Not an Echo helped secure Barry Goldwater's nomination. With sales of more than 3 million copies, the book established her as a national voice within the conservative movement. But it was Schlafly's bid to defeat the Equal Rights Amendment that gained her a grassroots following. Her anti-ERA crusade attracted hundreds of thousands of women into the conservative fold and earned her a name as feminism's most ardent opponent. In the 1970s, Schlafly founded the Eagle Forum, a Washington-based conservative policy organization that today claims a membership of 50,000 women. Filled with fresh insights into these and other initiatives, Phyllis Schlafly and Grassroots Conservatism provides a telling profile of one of the most influential activists in recent history. Sure to invite spirited debate, it casts new light on a major shift in American politics, the emergence of the Republican Right.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Mai 2019) 0aConservatismzUnited States. 0aConservativeszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aPolitical activistszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aWomen political activistszUnited StatesvBiography. 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691187976zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691187976.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGB